  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate the function \\( a^x \\) (where \\( a \\) is a constant) with respect to \\( x \\), we can use the fact that the derivative of \\( a^x \\) is given by:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \\ln(a)\n\\]\n\nNow, let's differentiate \\( a^x \\) up to 4 terms:\n\n1. **First Derivative**:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \\ln(a)\n   \\]\n\n2. **Second Derivative**:\n   Using the product rule on \\( a^x \\ln(a) \\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x \\ln(a)) = a^x \\ln(a) \\cdot \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2\n   \\]\n\n3. **Third Derivative**:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^3}{dx^3}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x (\\ln(a))^2) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2 \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3\n   \\]\n\n4. **Fourth Derivative**:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^4}{dx^4}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x (\\ln(a))^3) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3 \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4\n   \\]\n\nPutting it all together, we have:\n\n1. \\( \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \\ln(a) \\)\n2. \\( \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2 \\)\n3. \\( \\frac{d^3}{dx^3}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3 \\)\n4. \\( \\frac{d^4}{dx^4}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4 \\)\n\nThese are the derivatives of \\( a^x \\) up to four terms.",
